document:
Lucy is the first space mission to explore a diverse population of small bodies known as the Jupiter Trojan asteroids. These remnants of our early solar system are trapped on stable orbits associated with - but not close to - the giant planet Jupiter. Trojan asteroids orbit in two "swarms" that lead and follow Jupiter in its orbit around the Sun and are thought to be comparable in number to the objects in the main asteroid belt between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter.

Over its 12-year mission, Lucy will explore a record-breaking number of asteroids: it will fly by two (plus a newly discovered satellite) in the belt of asteroids that circle the Sun between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, and then eight Trojans, which includes five asteroid targets and the satellites of three of those. Lucy also will fly by Earth three times to get a push from its gravity, making it the first spacecraft to return to the vicinity of Earth from the outer solar system.

Good morning, everyone! Today, I have a wonderful story to share with you about a great adventure in space. Imagine you have a friend named Lucy who loves exploring and discovering new things. Lucy is a special kind of explorer because she travels through space to learn about rocks called asteroids.

These asteroids are like the tiny crumbs left over from when our solar system, which includes the Sun and all the planets, was very, very young. They float around in space, especially near a big planet called Jupiter. But they are not very close to Jupiter; they just follow it around like little ducklings following their mama duck!

Lucy’s mission is to visit and learn about these asteroids. She will travel for a long, long time—12 years! During her journey, she will visit a lot of these space rocks. She will see two asteroids in a place between Mars and Jupiter where many asteroids live, and then she will visit eight more that follow Jupiter. She will even see some asteroids that have little moons!

But Lucy needs some help to get around. Just like you might get a push on a swing to go higher, Lucy will come back to Earth three times to get a little push from Earth's gravity. This helps her travel further into space.

Lucy’s adventure is very special because she will visit more asteroids than anyone has before. By learning about these space rocks, Lucy will help scientists understand more about how our solar system was formed a long, long time ago.

So, Lucy is like a brave explorer who goes on an amazing journey to learn and discover, helping us all understand our big, wonderful space neighborhood better. Isn’t that exciting?

### NASA's Lucy Mission: An Unprecedented Journey to Explore Trojan Asteroids

NASA has embarked on an ambitious mission named "Lucy," designed to study the previously uncharted Trojan asteroids that share Jupiter's orbit. This groundbreaking 12-year mission aims to provide new insights into the formation and evolution of our solar system by surveying these primordial space rocks.

The Lucy spacecraft, named after the fossilized human ancestor whose discovery shed light on human evolution, will visit a total of ten asteroids. The mission schedule includes encounters with two main-belt asteroids located between Mars and Jupiter, followed by an in-depth exploration of eight Trojan asteroids that trail and lead Jupiter in its orbit.

One of the critical aspects of the Lucy mission is its use of gravity assists—three strategic flybys of Earth that will provide the necessary momentum to propel the spacecraft deeper into space. These gravitational boosts are akin to receiving a push on a swing, allowing Lucy to traverse the vast distances required to reach its diverse targets.

The significance of the Lucy mission cannot be overstated. By examining these ancient celestial bodies, Lucy will offer unprecedented data on the building blocks of the solar system, helping scientists piece together the complex history of planetary formation.

Lucy’s journey marks the first mission to the Trojans, making it a pioneer in asteroid exploration. This mission represents a monumental step forward in our quest to understand the origins of our cosmic neighborhood, promising to unlock secrets that have been preserved for billions of years.

### Key Mission Facts:
- **Mission Duration**: 12 years
- **Total Asteroids to be Visited**: 10 (2 main-belt asteroids and 8 Trojan asteroids)
- **Gravity Assists**: 3 Earth flybys
- **Purpose**: To study the composition and characteristics of Trojan asteroids, providing insights into the early solar system.

NASA's Lucy mission is poised to revolutionize our understanding of the solar system's history, making it one of the most anticipated space missions of the decade.

Arnold Schwarzenegger

Governor of California from 2003 to 2011

Significant Facts

Born: July 30, 1947 in Thal, Austria

Married: Maria Shriver on April 26, 1986 (The couple filed for divorce in 2011.)

Political Party: Republican

Arnold Schwarzenegger was born in Thal, Austria, a small village bordering the Styrian capital of Graz. He immigrated to the United States in 1968 and became a U.S. citizen in 1983.

Schwarzenegger earned a BA in Business and International Economics at the University of Wisconsin-Superior. He received an honorary Doctorate from the University of Wisconsin-Superior in 1996 and an honorary Doctorate from Chapman University in 2002.
    
An increasingly politically active Republican during the 1990s, Schwarzenegger ran for the California governorship and won when Gray Davis was recalled in 2003. Schwarzenegger was sworn in as the 38th Governor of California on November 17, 2003, following careers in body building, business and entertainment. Schwarzenegger was the first foreign-born governor of California since Irish-born Governor John G. Downey (Governor of California from 1860 to 1862). While governor, Schwarzenegger focused on reducing California's greenhouse gas emissions, increasing the minimum wage, and updating the workers' compensation system. He was also a proponent of physical education and after-school programs, and supported the After-School Education & Safety Act, which passed in 2002.

Once upon a time, in a tiny village far, far away called Thal, there was a little boy named Arnold. Arnold was full of dreams and wanted to do great things. As he grew up, he decided to move to a big, exciting place called America.

When Arnold got to America, he worked very hard and went to school to learn lots of important stuff about business and how the world works. He also loved to exercise and became very strong, just like a superhero! People admired him so much for his strength and hard work.

But Arnold didn't stop there. He wanted to help people even more, so he decided to become a leader. He ran for a very important job called 'Governor' in a big state called California. Guess what? He won! Arnold became the leader of California and worked hard to make it a better place.

As the governor, Arnold did many good things. He helped protect the air we breathe by reducing bad gases that can hurt our planet. He also made sure that people who work get paid fairly. Arnold cared a lot about children, just like you, and he supported programs that helped kids learn and stay safe after school.

So, you see, Arnold's story teaches us that if you dream big, work hard, and care for others, you can do amazing things and help make the world a better place. Remember, even someone from a tiny village can grow up to do great things!

The end.

**Arnold Schwarzenegger: From Thal to California's Governor**

**Thal, Austria** - In the quiet village of Thal, a young boy named Arnold Schwarzenegger harbored dreams of greatness. Born on July 30, 1947, Schwarzenegger's journey from this humble beginning to becoming a global icon and influential political leader is nothing short of remarkable.

Relocating to the United States, Schwarzenegger pursued higher education in business and developed a profound understanding of economic and political systems. Simultaneously, he dedicated himself to bodybuilding, achieving unprecedented success and earning the title of Mr. Olympia seven times.

Beyond his athletic achievements, Schwarzenegger sought to impact society on a broader scale. In 2003, he ran for the governorship of California, a state facing significant economic and environmental challenges. His successful bid led to his tenure as the 38th Governor of California from 2003 to 2011.

During his time in office, Schwarzenegger championed several key initiatives. He was instrumental in enacting legislation aimed at reducing greenhouse gas emissions, positioning California as a leader in environmental policy. Additionally, he focused on labor reforms to ensure fair wages and supported after-school programs to enhance the safety and education of children.

Schwarzenegger's legacy as governor reflects his commitment to public service and his belief in the power of hard work and visionary leadership. His life story serves as an inspiration, demonstrating that with dedication and a passion for helping others, extraordinary achievements are possible.

From the small village of Thal to the political helm of California, Arnold Schwarzenegger's journey underscores the impact of dreaming big and striving for excellence.

**End of Article**
